lture, and as domestic workers, are all examined using a wide range of printed and unpublished sources from across England. The roles village women performed in the informal rural economy (household labour, gathering resources and exploiting systems of barterand exchange) are also assessed. Changes in women's economic opportunities are explored, alongside the implications of region, age, marital status, number of children in the family and local custom; women's economic contribution to the rural labouring household is established as a critical part of family subsistence, despite criticism of such work and the rise in male wages after 1850. NICOLA VERDON is a Research Fellow in the Rural History Centre, University of Reading.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgricultural laborerszEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aRural womenzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen employeeszEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenxEmploymentzEnglandxHistoryy19th century. 4aModern History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh  aDay Labourers.  aDomestic Workers.  aEconomic Opportunities.  aFamily Economy.  aFamily Subsistence.  aFarm Servants.  aMarital Status.  aNineteenth-Century England.  aRural Women Workers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978184615150740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781846151507423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781846151507/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles